{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567816"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:07:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:07:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19448"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19448"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.26,0.12,0.17,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12175"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84678"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12175"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19448"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68965"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1440"},{"type":"tags","id":"4236"},{"type":"tags","id":"4267"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28798"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30663"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38637"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46316"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84678"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-centimetre lump over the nape of his neck that appeared three months ago. The lump has not changed in size and remains asymptomatic. His main concern is the appearance of the lump. He has a history of multiple similar lumps on his chest and back. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The lump is one centimetre in diameter with no surrounding erythema. It is non-fluctuant but compressible. It has a dark central punctum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following inherited conditions is most likely to be associated with these skin lesions?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Neurofibromatosis","Familial adenomatous polyposis","Peutz-Jeghers syndrome","PTEN hamartoma syndrome","Lynch syndrome"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical features described are consistent with an epidermoid cyst (previously known as a sebaceous cyst). The presence of multiple epidermoid cysts, particularly when associated with a central punctum, should raise suspicion for Gardner syndrome, which is a variant of \u003Cstrong\u003Efamilial adenomatous polyposis\u003C/strong\u003E. Gardner syndrome is characterised by colonic polyps, osteomas, and soft tissue tumours including epidermoid cysts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurofibromatosis\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with caf\u00e9-au-lait spots, axillary freckling, and multiple soft, flesh-coloured neurofibromas. These lesions typically lack a central punctum and have a different consistency from epidermoid cysts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeutz-Jeghers syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by mucocutaneous pigmentation, particularly around the lips and oral mucosa, along with hamartomatous polyps throughout the gastrointestinal tract. It is not typically associated with epidermoid cysts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPTEN hamartoma syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (including Cowden syndrome) is associated with multiple hamartomas, trichilemmomas, and acral keratoses. While it can present with multiple skin lesions, these are typically different in appearance from epidermoid cysts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELynch syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (hereditary non-polyposis colorectal cancer) is primarily associated with colorectal and other internal malignancies. It does not have characteristic cutaneous manifestations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of multiple epidermoid cysts should prompt consideration of colonoscopy to screen for familial adenomatous polyposis, particularly in young patients. Early detection is crucial as FAP carries a nearly 100% lifetime risk of colorectal cancer if left untreated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Multiple epidermoid cysts with central puncta may be associated with Gardner syndrome, a variant of familial adenomatous polyposis.","Epidermoid cysts are benign lesions containing keratin and lined by stratified squamous epithelium.","The presence of a central punctum is a key distinguishing feature of epidermoid cysts."],"references":["Burger B, Cattani N, Trueb S, de Lorenzo R, Albertini M, Bontognali E, Itin C, Schaub N, Itin PH, Heinimann K. Prevalence of skin lesions in familial adenomatous polyposis: a marker for presymptomatic diagnosis? Oncologist. 2011;16(12):1698-705. doi: 10.1634/theoncologist.2011-0244. Epub 2011 Dec 1. PMID: 22135120; PMCID: PMC3248768."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68965"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19448"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68965"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-10T10:28:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-10T10:29:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12175"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84678"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.